<Document>
<name>Romantische Straße</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Romantische Straße</h2><p><i>Germany · Würzburg to Füssen via Rothenburg, Dinkelsbühl, Augsburg, Schwangau</i></p><p><b>460 km through medieval Bavaria from Franconian wine country to Ludwig II's fairytale castle.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>297 km (184 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>6–8 hrs end-to-end; ideally 3–5 days</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>April–October; Christmas markets late November–December</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Tour-bus density in Rothenburg, summer crowds, parking, slow tractor traffic on rural sections</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>305</td></tr></table><hr><p>Created in 1950 as a marketing concept to lure American tourists to a Bavaria flattened by war — and it worked. The route stitches together genuinely medieval towns that had been bypassed by industrialization (and bombing): Rothenburg on its hill above the Tauber, Dinkelsbühl with its rainbow-colored gables, Nördlingen built inside a 25 km-wide meteor crater. It ends at Neuschwanstein, Ludwig II's castle that inspired Disney. The 'Romantic' in the name is the 19th-century Romantic-movement sense — picturesque, medieval, idealized — not the Valentine sense. Drive in shoulder season; even Rothenburg sleeps off-season.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Würzburg Residenz</b> — UNESCO Rococo palace (1720–44) of the Würzburg prince-bishops. Tiepolo's ceiling fresco above the staircase is the largest in the world. Würzburg's Franconian Riesling is exceptional.</li><li><b>Rothenburg ob der Tauber</b> — Walled medieval town, fully preserved (then carefully reconstructed after WWII bombing). Walk the wall complete circuit, 90 min. Christmas Museum operates year-round.</li><li><b>Dinkelsbühl</b> — Less visited than Rothenburg, just as preserved — 700-year-old townscape, rainbow gables, complete city wall. Authoritative consensus: more atmospheric, fewer tour buses.</li><li><b>Nördlingen</b> — Built inside the Nördlinger Ries — a 25 km-wide meteor crater from 14.6 million years ago. The town's St. Georg church tower contains rocks made from the impact. Climb 350 steps for panorama into the crater rim.</li><li><b>Augsburg / Fuggerei</b> — Founded by the Roman emperor in 15 BC. The Fuggerei (1521) is the world's oldest still-functioning social housing complex — rent for residents has been 1 Rhine guilder per year (about €0.88) for 500 years.</li><li><b>Wieskirche</b> — UNESCO Rococo pilgrimage church (1745–54) standing alone in a meadow. Inside is one of the masterpieces of European Baroque — intentional theatrical light, painted clouds dissolving into real ones.</li><li><b>Schloss Neuschwanstein</b> — Ludwig II's castle, 1869–86, built when castles were already 300 years out of fashion. Inspired Disney's Sleeping Beauty Castle. Reservations essential; tours sold out weeks ahead in summer.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
